This paper is likely to belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category as it deals with computing achievable information rates for a fiber channel. It may also belong to the Networked and Distributed Systems (cs.NI) sub-category as it deals with communication over a channel. The use of machine learning suggests that it may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper may also belong to the Signal Processing (cs.SD) sub-category as it deals with processing signals in a communication system. Finally, it may belong to the Communications (cs.COM) sub-category as it deals with communication systems.
